<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-05-21T11:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-05-21T11:45:00-05:00" n="332" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d332">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/4858: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-05-21T11:00:00-05:45"><hi rend="italic">May 21,
                                        1927—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 2:04
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>139. Sacasa with 26 followers left last night for Puerto Limon on
                            steamship <hi rend="italic">Wawa</hi>. They may be expected to be joined
                            by Nicaraguan Liberals there and to combine in efforts to embarrass the
                            Diaz Government.<note n="75" xml:id="d332fn75">By a decree issued at
                                Puerto Cabezas, May 20, 1927, Dr. Sacasa announced the termination
                                of his regime, organized in that neighborhood Dec. 1, 1926 (file No.
                                817.00/4918).</note></p>
                        <p>Repeated to Costa Rica.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>